26c90-ed303 | 2026-06-29T10:58:01Z | session:26c909a1-6c07-4761-bac5-6e880cd7a063 | **"Read" in the spins = the *projection* step: turning the claim log into the guide `.md` files on disk.** That happens at **capture time** (or a periodic compaction pass) — the same moment capture runs today, which is *not* latency-sensitive. \n  \n The two moments, kept distinct: \n  \n | Moment | What happens | Latency sensitivity | \n |---|---|---| \n | **Capture / compaction** ("read" in the spins) | claims → rendered guide `.md` written to disk | Not hot — runs on SessionEnd / on a schedule | \n | **Inject** (the SELECT + COMPILE pipeline) | reads the already-materialized guide `.md`, synthesizes a briefing into Claude's context | **Hot** — fires on every prompt | \n  \n So in all three spins, the projection produces **on-disk guide markdown**, exactly like the files you have now. **Inject is completely unchanged** — it reads those `.md` files via SELECT→COMPILE just as it does today, fast, with no idea how they were generated. \n  \n This is actually a load-bearing design rule worth stating explicitly: **you must never defer projection to inject-time.** If a "pure event-sourcing" reading tempted you to "project the guide on demand when inject needs it," you'd be dropping an expensive LLM render onto the pre-prompt hot path — the exact latency mistake we fixed earlier with the gate. The discipline is: **guides are always materialized to disk at capture/compaction; inject only ever reads materialized files.** \n  \n So when I called Spin 2's reads "expensive" — that cost is paid at **capture time** (every render passes the full claim history through an LLM), amortized off the hot path, *not* paid per user prompt. That's also why the test harness calls `project()` once to write `guides/*.md` and scores those files: it's modeling the capture-side projection, and inject isn't in the experiment at all. \n 
