be9ee-64087 | 2026-06-29T11:10:29Z | session:be9ee788-301d-4758-9260-69dce3ae35b9 |  \n A **retrieve-then-rerank** design that replaces "LLM scans a flat list" with two stages: \n  \n **Stage 1 — RECALL (embeddings, mechanical, no LLM).** The project already maintains a `vec_chunks` embedding index over the wiki (it's what inject's RAG uses). For each claim: embed the claim text, query the index for the **top-K most semantically similar existing guides** (cosine). That yields a tiny, high-relevance candidate set — *the guides this claim is actually near in meaning, regardless of title wording.* \n  \n **Stage 2 — RERANK (cheap LLM, constrained).** Hand the LLM **only those top-K candidates** + the claim, and ask "which of these is the home, or is it genuinely NEW?" The reasoning step catches what embeddings miss — semantically-distant-but-co-topical facts (*"use optimistic locking"* and *"profile edits race"* belong together but embed far apart) — but now it's a small, pre-filtered choice, not a 132-guide haystack scan. \n  [...] - Files changed: `src/route_recall.rs` (new), `src/capture.rs` (ROUTE rewrite + preamble), `src/main.rs` (mod decl). \n - My commits: `6d2f585` (retrieve-then-rerank), `9192dab` (rerank must trust candidates), `8bda0ab` (same-subsystem = merge). \n - Two commits I did NOT author are on the branch from the orchestrator (`pablof7z` identity, 00:14–00:15): `a2c3e93` a 3-line `slice_transcript_ranges` inverted-range panic guard, and `5a9fffd` a clean master merge whose entire delta is that guard. The guard never triggered (run exited 0); my final e2e + unit run rebuilt release from current HEAD and passed, so validation holds for HEAD, not just my pre-merge commits. [...] 🔍 ANALYSIS: ROUTE's flat all-guides list gave the LLM no similarity signal, forcing an unbeatable split-vs-merge tension. The fix splits ROUTE into RECALL (in-memory cosine over live guides) + RERANK (LLM picks among each claim's top-K candidates or NEW). The decisive non-obvious findings during tuning: (1) the bottleneck was rerank-*trust*, not recall or τ — recall surfaced the right guide and the LLM minted NEW anyway, twice; (2) τ is structurally the wrong knob (it's global and cannot encode "timeout is a feature of inject but compile is a distinct mechanism" per-pair) — both fixes were preamble edits, not threshold tuning. \n  \n ⚡ ACTIONS: Added `src/route_recall.rs` (recall + cosine + 7 unit tests). Rewrote the ROUTE block in `src/capture.rs` to embed live guides in-memory at route time (freshness-correct — never the stale `index.db`), recall top-K per claim, and feed each claim only its own candidates. Recalibrated `ROUTE_PREAMBLE` twice: trust semantically-close candidates, and treat same-subsystem facets as MERGE not NEW. Ran the archeologist under full private-HOME isolation to dodge a concurrent external `pc archeologist` run that was racing on the shared real config. [...] ## The one honest wrinkle (and it's real) \n  \n **Freshness — the same problem we just fixed for the *text* index, but harder for embeddings.** We fixed ROUTE reading a stale `_index.md` by scanning live guide frontmatter (`read_index_live`). Embeddings can't be "scanned live" cheaply — a guide written earlier in the same session window isn't *embedded* yet, so embedding-recall would be blind to just-created siblings unless we **embed-on-write** (incrementally index each new guide immediately) or re-embed touched guides per session. That's the main engineering cost, and it's where a sloppy implementation would silently reintroduce dups. \n  [...] 1. ROUTE handed the LLM a flat list of all guides, so it matched on title words with no real similarity signal — splitting finely made near-dup slugs, merge-braking collapsed inject to 3 guides. \n 2. I split ROUTE into RECALL (embeddings) + RERANK (LLM): for each claim, cosine-rank the live guides in memory, surface the top-K, and let the LLM choose only among those or NEW. \n 3. Freshness was the critical invariant — I embed the live on-disk guides at route time, never the checkpoint `index.db`, so a session sees siblings written moments earlier; the logs confirmed later sessions recalling earlier guides.
