be9ee-eae45 | 2026-06-29T11:10:29Z | session:be9ee788-301d-4758-9260-69dce3ae35b9 | ## The headline: routing, not reconciliation, is the bottleneck \n  \n The thing we spent days designing — write-time vs read-time reconciliation — **barely mattered.** Every spin reconciles *within a single guide*. **None of them handles a topic that gets split across two slugs**, and that's what actually broke all three: \n  \n - Spin 3: the router made **11 guides for cli-tool (expected 6)** and **4 for data-pipeline (expected 6)** — fragmentation, with stale content stranded in dead slugs. \n - Spin 2 (purest ES) is **structurally the most exposed**: its read-time projector for slug X only sees X's claims, so if the superseding fact was routed to slug Y, the projector renders X's stale claim as current — it *can't even know* it was superseded. That cross-slug blindness is largely what it spent 73 minutes failing to work around. \n - Spin 1 has the same per-slug scoping but masks it better because it supersedes at write within the slug. \n  \n **Conclusion: the highest-leverage fix is ROUTE — canonical, stable topic→slug so an update lands where the original claim lives. It's upstream of the entire write-vs-read debate, and it's what determines whether any spin's reconciliation even gets a chance.** \n  [...] **Why now specifically:** expanding coverage *used* to be dangerous — more sessions meant more fragmentation/accretion. **Routing is now clean (embedding router, 0 dups), and the authority model is keep-everything/metadata-only**, so the extra agentic-session volume gets routed and reconciled cleanly instead of exploding into duplicates. The ordering worked out: fix routing → then safely open the floodgates. \n  [...] ## Verdict: Phase 2 topic routing does NOT organize (confirmed) \n  \n The ratio is **pinned at exactly 1.00 across two checkpoints** — 33 guides/33 topics at session 45, then 48 guides/48 topics at session 77. **Zero topics ever held more than one guide.** This is categorical, not cold-start noise: every guide invents its own topic, so the `topic` field is functioning as a redundant second slug, not a grouping. The flat-pile problem was promoted one level up, exactly as the plan warned. \n  \n **Root cause (verified in the merged code):** the RERANK prompt is correctly written — it renders the catalog grouped by topic and instructs "reuse existing topics" — but topic selection is **prompt-bias only**, while guide-slug selection gets **embedding recall**. Topic reuse has no structural enforcement, so it fails the same way the deleted "~25-30 guides" count target did. The project's own memory predicted this: *prompt-tuning a split/merge decision fails; that's why the embedding router was built.* Topics never got the router treatment. \n 
