fbd3d-554ed | 2026-06-29T11:44:52Z | session:fbd3d6f8-1b55-4271-aaf4-de0790b5120b | **1. The debounce gate** (`capture_debounce_secs`, default `300` — `config.rs:200`) \n  \n This is the "gate" you're thinking of. It's a *trailing* debounce, not session-end: \n  \n - On each trigger (`capture --in`), it writes a pending file stamped with `scheduled_at_secs = now`, **SIGTERMs any in-flight debounce process** for that session (`capture.rs:1902-1906`), and spawns a fresh detached `capture --deferred <session>`. \n - That deferred runner sleeps 300s (`capture.rs:1976`), then re-reads the pending file. If a newer trigger arrived in the meantime, it bails and lets the newer process win; otherwise it runs the actual wiki capture. \n  \n Net effect: capture fires **5 minutes after the last trigger settles**, and repeated activity keeps pushing the gate out. [...] **2. The agent timeout** (`capture.rs:1576`: `Duration::from_secs(300) // 5 min max`) \n  \n Separately, once the wiki capture agent *does* run, it gets killed if it exceeds 300s (`capture: wiki agent timed out after 300s`). [...] One thing to keep in mind given how the debounce works: each Stop resets the timer. So with `60`, capture runs 1 minute after your *last* turn — but if you send another message within that minute, the pending one is SIGTERMed and the clock restarts. That's the intended behavior (it coalesces a back-and-forth session into a single capture), just worth knowing that "1 minute after stop" means 1 minute of actual silence, not 1 minute after the first stop.
